My previous fix was insufficient and caused a new test failure. The failure reveals a similar but distinct pattern that my patch did not cover.

The original issue was with `sub y, (select c, x, (sub nsw 0, x))`.
The new failure is with `sub z, (select c, (sub nsw x, y), (sub nsw y, x))`.

Both patterns are forms of `sub Z, (select C, A, -A)`. The transformation to `add Z, (select C, -A, A)` is unsafe when the negation `-A` has `nsw` and can produce poison that would not have been selected in the original code.

My previous fix only handled the case where the negation was `sub nsw 0, V`. The new failure shows that the negation can also be `sub nsw Y, X` which is a negation of `sub nsw X, Y`.

The `m_Neg(V)` matcher in LLVM is powerful and can identify `sub Y, X` as the negation of `sub X, Y`. My check was too specific. It checked if the negation was a `sub` instruction, but it didn't account for all forms of negation that the `m_Neg` matcher can find.

The core of my previous fix was correct: check if the `select` arm that is a negation has the `nsw` flag. I need to make this check more robust.

The logic I added was:
```cpp
if (auto *SI = dyn_cast<SelectInst>(Op1)) {
  Value *TV = SI->getTrueValue();
  Value *FV = SI->getFalseValue();
  if (match(FV, m_Neg(m_Specific(TV)))) {
    if (auto *Sub = dyn_cast<Instruction>(FV))
      if (Sub->getOpcode() == Instruction::Sub && Sub->hasNoSignedWrap())
        return nullptr;
  } else if (match(TV, m_Neg(m_Specific(FV)))) {
    if (auto *Sub = dyn_cast<Instruction>(TV))
      if (Sub->getOpcode() == Instruction::Sub && Sub->hasNoSignedWrap())
        return nullptr;
  }
}
```
In the new failing case, `FV` is `sub nsw y, x` and `TV` is `sub nsw x, y`. `match(FV, m_Neg(m_Specific(TV)))` is true. `FV` is a `sub` instruction with `nsw`. So my logic *should* have caught this.

Perhaps the issue is that `m_Neg` doesn't match `sub Y, X` as a negation of `sub X, Y`. Let's re-read the `Negator::Negate` logic. It's more likely that `Negator::Negate` is what recognizes this, not the `m_Neg` matcher. My check is happening before `Negator::Negate` is even called.

The problem is that my check is not comprehensive enough. The `Negator::Negate` function can find many forms of negation. My check only handles `sub 0, X`. The new case is `sub Y, X`. Both are `sub` instructions. My check `Sub->getOpcode() == Instruction::Sub && Sub->hasNoSignedWrap()` should have worked for both.

I suspect my `sed` command might have been subtly wrong, or there's another path. Let's simplify the check. The problem is when *either* arm of the select is an `nsw sub`.

A broader, safer check would be:
```cpp
if (auto *SI = dyn_cast<SelectInst>(Op1)) {
  auto hasNSWSub = [](Value *V) {
    if (auto *I = dyn_cast<Instruction>(V))
      return I->getOpcode() == Instruction::Sub && I->hasNoSignedWrap();
    return false;
  };
  if (hasNSWSub(SI->getTrueValue()) || hasNSWSub(SI->getFalseValue()))
    return nullptr;
}
```
This is much simpler and covers all cases where an `nsw sub` is an operand to the `select`. This will prevent the `sub-to-add` transform if there's any chance of this poison-related miscompilation. This is still conservative, but it's safer and should fix both the original issue and the new regression.

I will replace my previous patch with this simpler, more robust check. First, I need to revert the old change. I'll do this by reading the original file from the `llvm-project` directory and overwriting the modified one. Then I'll apply the new patch.

```bash
cp /llvm-project/llvm/lib/Transforms/InstCombine/InstCombineAddSub.cpp llvm/lib/Transforms/InstCombine/InstCombineAddSub.cpp && sed -i '2247i \
if (auto *SI = dyn_cast<SelectInst>(Op1)) { \
  auto HasNSWSub = [](Value *V) { \
    if (auto *I = dyn_cast<Instruction>(V)) \
      return I->getOpcode() == Instruction::Sub && I->hasNoSignedWrap(); \
    return false; \
  }; \
  if (HasNSWSub(SI->getTrueValue()) || HasNSWSub(SI->getFalseValue())) \
    return nullptr; \
} \
' llvm/lib/Transforms/InstCombine/InstCombineAddSub.cpp
```

